Lag, lead, and running aggregates.

Two more families of window functions, both built on the frame.

First, the offset functions — lag and lead. Within a partition, lag, with a column, an offset n, and a default, looks back n rows. And lead, with the same arguments, looks forward n rows. Both return the default — or null — at the partition boundary. These are perfect for delta calculations, like days since the previous transaction, or time to the next event.

Second, the running aggregates, which are all about the frame. Rows-between counts physical row positions, relative to the current row. Range-between, by contrast, counts the value range of the order-by column — which is what you want when the order-by column is a number or a date, and you want something like all rows within plus-or-minus seven days.

There are three frames worth memorizing. A cumulative frame is rows-between unbounded-preceding and current-row. An n-row trailing window is rows-between negative-n and current-row. And a centered n-row window is rows-between negative-n and positive-n.

And if you remember one thing from this section, make it this — rows versus range is the most-tested window distinction. Rows is a physical row offset. Range is a value offset.
